1
00:02:21,300 --> 00:02:22,900
Rosebud.

2
00:02:59,500 --> 00:03:01,600
News on the March.

3
00:03:20,300 --> 00:03:22,300
{y:i}Legendary was the Xanadu...

4
00:03:22,300 --> 00:03:25,800
{y:i}...where Kubla Khan decreed
{y:i}his stately pleasure dome.

5
00:03:25,900 --> 00:03:29,200
{y:i}Today almost as legendary
{y:i}as Florida's Xanadu...

6
00:03:29,300 --> 00:03:31,500
{y:i}...the world's largest
{y:i}private pleasure ground.

7
00:03:34,200 --> 00:03:37,300
{y:i}Here on the deserts of the Gulf Coast,
{y:i}a private mountain...

8
00:03:37,400 --> 00:03:39,300
{y:i}...was commissioned and successfully built.

9
00:03:39,400 --> 00:03:42,800
{y:i}One hundred thousand trees,
{y:i}twenty thousand tons of marble...

10
00:03:42,900 --> 00:03:45,400
{y:i}...are the ingredients
{y:i}of Xanadu's mountain.

11
00:03:46,400 --> 00:03:48,700
{y:i}Contents of Xanadu痴 palace:

12
00:03:48,800 --> 00:03:52,800
{y:i}Paintings, pictures, statues,
{y:i}various stones of other palaces.

13
00:03:53,200 --> 00:03:55,000
{y:i}A collection of everything.

14
00:03:55,100 --> 00:03:58,200
{y:i}So big it can never
{y:i}be catalogued or appraised.

15
00:03:58,300 --> 00:04:01,900
{y:i}Enough for 10 museums,
{y:i}the loot of the world.

16
00:04:05,400 --> 00:04:07,300
{y:i}Xanadu's livestock...

17
00:04:08,300 --> 00:04:13,600
{y:i}...the fowl of the air, the fish of the sea,
{y:i}the beast of the field and jungle...

18
00:04:13,900 --> 00:04:17,900
{y:i}...two of each,
{y:i}the biggest private zoo since Noah.

19
00:04:18,600 --> 00:04:20,300
{y:i}Like the Pharaohs...

20
00:04:20,500 --> 00:04:24,300
{y:i}...Xanadu's landlord leaves many stones
{y:i}to mark his grave.

21
00:04:25,800 --> 00:04:27,300
{y:i}Since the Pyramids...

22
00:04:27,500 --> 00:04:30,100
{y:i}...Xanadu is the costliest monument...

23
00:04:30,100 --> 00:04:32,500
{y:i}...a man has built to himself.

24
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,500
{y:i}Here in Xanadu last week...

25
00:04:47,900 --> 00:04:50,700
{y:i}...Xanadu's landlord was laid to rest.

26
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:53,600
{y:i}A potent figure of our century...

27
00:04:53,700 --> 00:04:55,800
{y:i}...America's Kubla Khan:

28
00:04:56,200 --> 00:04:58,000
{y:i}Charles Foster Kane.

29
00:05:24,300 --> 00:05:29,100
{y:i}Its humble beginnings,
{y:i}in this ramshackle building, a dying daily.

30
00:05:29,300 --> 00:05:31,700
{y:i}Kane's empire, in its glory...

31
00:05:31,900 --> 00:05:35,700
{y:i}...held dominion over 37 newspapers,
{y:i}two syndicates...

32
00:05:35,900 --> 00:05:40,300
{y:i}...a radio network,
{y:i}an empire upon an empire.

33
00:05:40,600 --> 00:05:44,300
{y:i}The first of grocery stores, paper mills...

34
00:05:44,500 --> 00:05:49,900
{y:i}...apartment buildings,
{y:i}factories, forests, ocean liners.

35
00:05:49,900 --> 00:05:53,200
{y:i}An empire through which for 50 years...

36
00:05:53,300 --> 00:05:55,600
{y:i}...flowed in an unending stream...

37
00:05:55,900 --> 00:05:58,900
{y:i}...the wealth of the Earth's
{y:i}third richest gold mine.

38
00:06:00,300 --> 00:06:03,300
{y:i}Famed in American legend
{y:i}is the origin of the Kane fortune.

39
00:06:03,400 --> 00:06:08,800
{y:i}How, to boarding housekeeper Mary Kane,
{y:i}by a defaulting boarder, in 1868...

40
00:06:08,800 --> 00:06:12,500
{y:i}...was left the supposedly worthless deed
{y:i}to an abandoned mineshaft:

41
00:06:12,600 --> 00:06:15,600
{y:i}The Colorado Lode.

42
00:06:15,700 --> 00:06:19,700
{y:i}Fifty-seven years later,
{y:i}before a congressional investigation...

43
00:06:19,700 --> 00:06:23,100
{y:i}... Walter P. Thatcher,
{y:i}grand old man of Wall Street...

44
00:06:23,100 --> 00:06:26,700
{y:i}...for years chief target
{y:i}of Kane papers' attacks on trusts...

45
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:29,100
{y:i}...recalls a journey he made as a youth.

46
00:06:29,200 --> 00:06:32,500
My firm had been appointed trustee
by Mrs. Kane...

47
00:06:32,500 --> 00:06:34,700
...for a large fortune she recently acquired.

48
00:06:34,800 --> 00:06:38,700
It was her wish that I take charge
of this boy, Charles Foster Kane.

49
00:06:38,800 --> 00:06:43,400
Chief, is it not, that on this occasion,
Charles Foster Kane...

50
00:06:43,500 --> 00:06:48,100
...personally attacked you after striking you
in the stomach with a sled?

51
00:06:48,600 --> 00:06:51,400
I shall read to the committee
a prepared statement...

52
00:06:51,500 --> 00:06:56,700
...which I have brought with me,
and then refuse to answer questions.

53
00:06:57,200 --> 00:07:00,400
Mr. Charles Foster Kane,
in every essence of his social beliefs...

54
00:07:00,500 --> 00:07:03,300
...and by the dangerous manner
he has persistently attacked...

55
00:07:03,400 --> 00:07:05,600
...American traditions of private property...

56
00:07:05,700 --> 00:07:07,900
...initiative and opportunity
for advancement...

57
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:11,700
...is, in fact, nothing more or less
than a communist.

58
00:07:11,900 --> 00:07:14,200
{y:i}That same month in Union Square....

59
00:07:14,300 --> 00:07:16,900
{y:i}The words "Charles Foster Kane"...

60
00:07:16,900 --> 00:07:20,300
{y:i}...are a menace
{y:i}to every workingman in this land.

61
00:07:20,600 --> 00:07:25,800
{y:i}He is today what he has always been
{y:i}and always will be: a fascist.

62
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:28,000
{y:i}And still another opinion....

63
00:07:44,300 --> 00:07:47,700
{y:i}Kane urged his country's entry
{y:i}into one war...

64
00:07:47,900 --> 00:07:50,400
{y:i}...opposed participation in another.

65
00:07:50,600 --> 00:07:54,300
{y:i}Won the election
{y:i}to one American president at least.

66
00:07:54,500 --> 00:07:57,000
{y:i}Spoke for millions of Americans.

67
00:07:57,900 --> 00:08:00,400
{y:i}Was hated by as many more.

68
00:08:00,700 --> 00:08:04,100
{y:i}For 40 years appeared in Kane newsprint...

69
00:08:04,400 --> 00:08:08,500
{y:i}...no public issue
{y:i}on which Kane papers took no stand.

70
00:08:08,900 --> 00:08:14,100
{y:i}No public man whom Kane himself
{y:i}did not support or denounce.

71
00:08:14,100 --> 00:08:18,000
{y:i}Often support, then denounce.

72
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:29,300
{y:i}Twice married, twice divorced.

73
00:08:29,600 --> 00:08:31,800
{y:i}First to a president's niece...

74
00:08:31,900 --> 00:08:34,800
{y:i}...Emily Norton, who left him in 1916.

75
00:08:35,400 --> 00:08:38,800
{y:i}Died 1918 in a motor accident
{y:i}with their son.

76
00:08:41,100 --> 00:08:43,400
{y:i}Sixteen years after his first marriage...

77
00:08:43,500 --> 00:08:45,700
{y:i}...two weeks after his first divorce...

78
00:08:45,900 --> 00:08:48,000
{y:i}...Kane married Susan Alexander...

79
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:51,200
{y:i}...singer, at the Town Hall
{y:i}in Trenton, New Jersey.

80
00:08:51,900 --> 00:08:57,000
{y:i}For wife two,
{y:i}one-time opera-singing Susan Alexander...

81
00:08:57,200 --> 00:09:00,300
{y:i}...Kane built
{y:i}Chicago's Municipal Opera House.

82
00:09:00,400 --> 00:09:02,700
{y:i}Cost: $3 million.

83
00:09:02,800 --> 00:09:08,700
{y:i}Conceived for Susan Alexander Kane,
{y:i}half-finished before she divorced him...

84
00:09:08,800 --> 00:09:10,700
{y:i}...the still unfinished...

85
00:09:10,900 --> 00:09:12,200
{y:i}...Xanadu.

86
00:09:12,300 --> 00:09:15,400
{y:i}Cost: No man can say.

87
00:09:18,600 --> 00:09:21,700
{y:i}Kane, molder of mass opinion
{y:i}though he was...

88
00:09:21,900 --> 00:09:24,500
{y:i}...in all his life
{y:i}was never granted elective office...

89
00:09:24,500 --> 00:09:26,200
{y:i}...by the voters of his country.

90
00:09:26,300 --> 00:09:28,900
{y:i}But Kane papers were once strong indeed...

91
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:31,400
{y:i}...and once the prize seemed almost his.

92
00:09:31,700 --> 00:09:35,000
{y:i}In 1916, as independent candidate
{y:i}for governor...

93
00:09:35,100 --> 00:09:37,400
{y:i}...the best elements of the state
{y:i}behind him...

94
00:09:37,500 --> 00:09:42,100
{y:i}...the White House seemingly the next
{y:i}easy step in a lightning political career...

95
00:09:42,200 --> 00:09:45,900
{y:i}...then suddenly, less than one week
{y:i}before election...

96
00:09:46,500 --> 00:09:47,900
{y:i}...defeat.

97
00:09:47,900 --> 00:09:50,100
{y:i}Shameful, ignominious.

98
00:09:50,700 --> 00:09:54,100
{y:i}Defeat that set back for 20 years
{y:i}the cause of reform in the U.S...

99
00:09:54,200 --> 00:09:57,800
{y:i}...forever cancelled political chances
{y:i}for Charles Foster Kane.

100
00:10:00,800 --> 00:10:03,700
{y:i}Then, in the first year
{y:i}of the Great Depression...

101
00:10:04,300 --> 00:10:06,300
{y:i}...a Kane paper closes.

102
00:10:06,500 --> 00:10:10,000
{y:i}For Kane, in four short years, collapse.

103
00:10:10,400 --> 00:10:15,400
{y:i}Eleven Kane papers merged,
{y:i}more sold, scrapped.

104
00:10:24,700 --> 00:10:25,700
Is that correct?

105
00:10:25,800 --> 00:10:28,000
Don't believe everything you hear
on the radio.

106
00:10:28,100 --> 00:10:31,900
{y:i}-Read the Inquirer.
-How were business conditions in Europe?

107
00:10:31,900 --> 00:10:35,700
How did I find business conditions
in Europe, Mr. Bones?

108
00:10:35,800 --> 00:10:37,500
With great difficulty.

109
00:10:39,900 --> 00:10:41,500
Are you glad to be back?

110
00:10:41,500 --> 00:10:44,000
I'm always glad to be back.
I'm an American.

111
00:10:44,800 --> 00:10:47,300
Always been an American. Anything else?

112
00:10:47,300 --> 00:10:50,300
When I was a reporter,
we asked them quicker than that.

113
00:10:50,400 --> 00:10:52,800
What do you think
of the chances for war in Europe?

114
00:10:52,900 --> 00:10:57,000
I talked with the responsible leaders
of England, France, Germany and Italy.

115
00:10:57,100 --> 00:10:59,500
They're too intelligent
to embark on a project...

116
00:10:59,500 --> 00:11:01,900
...that would mean the end of civilization.

117
00:11:02,100 --> 00:11:05,500
You can take my word for it,
there will be no war.

118
00:11:09,700 --> 00:11:12,200
{y:i}Kane helped to change the world...

119
00:11:12,300 --> 00:11:14,900
{y:i}...but Kane's world now is history...

120
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:18,300
{y:i}...and the great yellow journalist himself
{y:i}lived to be history...

121
00:11:18,300 --> 00:11:20,600
{y:i}...outlived his power to make it.

122
00:11:21,400 --> 00:11:25,300
{y:i}Alone in his never-finished,
{y:i}already decaying pleasure palace...

123
00:11:25,500 --> 00:11:28,800
{y:i}...aloof, seldom visited,
{y:i}never photographed...

124
00:11:29,100 --> 00:11:32,900
{y:i}...an emperor of newsprint
{y:i}continued to direct his failing empire.

125
00:11:33,500 --> 00:11:36,200
{y:i}Vainly attempted to sway, as he once did...

126
00:11:36,500 --> 00:11:39,800
{y:i}...the destinies of a nation
{y:i}that had ceased to listen to him...

127
00:11:39,900 --> 00:11:41,500
{y:i}...ceased to trust him.

128
00:11:43,500 --> 00:11:47,300
{y:i}Then last week, as it must to all men...

129
00:11:48,300 --> 00:11:50,700
{y:i}...death came to Charles Foster Kane.

130
00:11:51,700 --> 00:11:53,500
News on the March.

131
00:11:58,400 --> 00:11:59,600
That's it.

132
00:12:00,300 --> 00:12:03,100
Stand by.
I'll tell you if we want to run it again.

133
00:12:03,100 --> 00:12:05,700
-How about it, Mr. Rawlston?
-How do you like it, boys?

134
00:12:05,800 --> 00:12:09,500
-Seventy years in a man's life.
-That's a lot to try to get into a newsreel.

135
00:12:09,600 --> 00:12:11,900
It's a good short,
but what it needs is an angle.

136
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:15,200
All we saw on that screen
was that Charles Foster Kane is dead.

137
00:12:15,200 --> 00:12:17,300
I know that. I read the papers.

138
00:12:17,300 --> 00:12:19,700
It isn't enough to tell us what a man did...

139
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:23,100
...you've got to tell us who he was.

140
00:12:23,100 --> 00:12:26,300
Wait a minute.
What were Kane's last words?

141
00:12:26,300 --> 00:12:28,200
Do you remember, boys?

142
00:12:28,300 --> 00:12:30,700
What were the last words
he said on Earth?

143
00:12:30,700 --> 00:12:32,700
Maybe he told us about himself
on his deathbed.

144
00:12:32,800 --> 00:12:35,800
-Maybe he didn't.
-All we saw was a big American.

145
00:12:35,900 --> 00:12:38,700
How did he differ from Ford,
Hearst or John Doe?

146
00:12:39,200 --> 00:12:41,300
I tell you, a man's dying words--

147
00:12:41,500 --> 00:12:43,300
What were they?
You don't read the papers.

148
00:12:43,400 --> 00:12:45,800
When Charles Foster Kane died,
he said one word:

149
00:12:45,900 --> 00:12:46,800
"Rosebud."

150
00:12:46,900 --> 00:12:48,600
That's all he said? Tough guy.

151
00:12:48,700 --> 00:12:50,900
Yes, "Rosebud." Just that one word.

152
00:12:51,200 --> 00:12:52,800
-But who is she?
-What was it?

153
00:12:52,900 --> 00:12:54,900
Here's a man
who could've been president...

154
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:57,200
...who was as loved,
hated and talked about...

155
00:12:57,300 --> 00:12:59,700
...as any man in our time,
but when he dies...

156
00:12:59,800 --> 00:13:02,000
...something is on his mind called Rosebud.

157
00:13:02,100 --> 00:13:04,400
-What does that mean?
-A racehorse he bet on once.

158
00:13:04,500 --> 00:13:06,700
-That didn't come in.
-But what was the race?

159
00:13:06,800 --> 00:13:07,900
Rosebud.

160
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:08,800
-Thompson.
-Yes.

161
00:13:08,900 --> 00:13:10,700
Hold this up a week, two if you must.

162
00:13:10,800 --> 00:13:12,500
Don't you think right after he's dead--

163
00:13:12,600 --> 00:13:15,600
Find out about Rosebud. Get in touch
with anybody who knew him...

164
00:13:15,700 --> 00:13:17,100
...or knew him well.

165
00:13:17,400 --> 00:13:19,000
That manager of his....

166
00:13:19,100 --> 00:13:21,400
Bernstein. His second wife.
She's still living.

167
00:13:21,500 --> 00:13:22,700
Susan Alexander Kane.

168
00:13:22,800 --> 00:13:25,500
-She runs a nightclub in Atlantic City.
-That's right.

169
00:13:25,600 --> 00:13:28,900
See them all. Get in touch with everybody
that ever worked for him...

170
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:31,700
...whoever loved him,
whoever hated his guts.

171
00:13:32,100 --> 00:13:34,900
I don't mean go through
the city directory of course.

172
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:36,500
I'll get on it right away.

173
00:13:36,600 --> 00:13:39,200
Good. Rosebud, dead or alive.

174
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:42,500
It will probably turn out to be
a very simple thing.

175
00:14:20,300 --> 00:14:21,800
Miss Alexander.

176
00:14:22,900 --> 00:14:25,100
This is Mr. Thompson, Miss Alexander.

177
00:14:25,300 --> 00:14:27,500
I want another drink, John.

178
00:14:30,300 --> 00:14:33,100
Right away.
Will you have something, Mr. Thompson?

179
00:14:33,100 --> 00:14:36,500
-I'll have a highball, please.
-Who told you you could sit down?

180
00:14:38,300 --> 00:14:40,200
I thought maybe we could have a talk.

181
00:14:40,300 --> 00:14:41,700
Think again.

182
00:14:42,900 --> 00:14:45,100
Can't you people leave me alone?

183
00:14:45,200 --> 00:14:47,300
I'm minding my own business,
you mind yours.

184
00:14:47,400 --> 00:14:50,200
If I could just have a talk with you,
Miss Alexander. I'd--

185
00:14:50,300 --> 00:14:51,700
Get out of here.

186
00:14:53,500 --> 00:14:54,700
Get out!

187
00:14:56,000 --> 00:14:57,400
-Sorry.
-Get out.

188
00:14:57,700 --> 00:15:00,100
-Maybe some other time.
-Get out.

189
00:15:10,600 --> 00:15:11,700
Gino.

190
00:15:13,500 --> 00:15:15,200
Get her another highball.

191
00:15:15,700 --> 00:15:18,100
She just won't talk to nobody,
Mr. Thompson.

192
00:15:18,200 --> 00:15:19,200
Okay.

193
00:15:21,300 --> 00:15:23,900
-Another double?
-Yeah.

194
00:15:24,800 --> 00:15:26,500
Hello, I want New York City.

195
00:15:26,500 --> 00:15:30,900
Courtland 79970.
This is Atlantic City 46827. All right.

196
00:15:33,900 --> 00:15:35,300
She's....

197
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:37,600
She'll snap out of it.

198
00:15:37,700 --> 00:15:40,900
Why, until he died, she'd just as soon
talk about Mr. Kane as any--

199
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:42,300
-Hello.
-Sooner.

200
00:15:42,400 --> 00:15:44,900
This is Thompson. Let me talk to the chief.

201
00:15:46,700 --> 00:15:48,600
Mr. Rawlston? She won't talk.

202
00:15:48,800 --> 00:15:51,500
The second Mrs. Kane.
About Rosebud or anything else.

203
00:15:51,600 --> 00:15:53,300
I'm calling from Atlantic City.

204
00:15:53,400 --> 00:15:56,900
Tomorrow I'll go to Philadelphia,
to Thatcher Library, to see his diary.

205
00:15:56,900 --> 00:15:58,300
They're expecting me.

206
00:15:58,300 --> 00:16:01,700
Then I've a meeting with his
general manager in New York. Bernstein.

207
00:16:01,800 --> 00:16:03,200
Then I'm coming back here.

208
00:16:03,300 --> 00:16:06,100
Yeah, I'll see everybody that's still alive.
Goodbye.

209
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:08,900
-Hey....
-John.

210
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:10,800
You just might be able to help me.

211
00:16:10,900 --> 00:16:14,400
When she used to talk about Mr. Kane,
did she ever mention Rosebud?

212
00:16:14,900 --> 00:16:16,200
"Rosebud"?

213
00:16:16,600 --> 00:16:18,500
Thank you, Mr. Thompson, thanks.

214
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:22,900
As a matter of fact, just the other day,
when the papers were full of it...

215
00:16:24,300 --> 00:16:26,300
...l asked her.

216
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:28,900
She never heard of Rosebud.

217
00:16:40,500 --> 00:16:44,900
The directors of the Thatcher Memorial
Library have asked me to remind you...

218
00:16:45,100 --> 00:16:47,700
...about the conditions
under which you may...

219
00:16:47,700 --> 00:16:50,700
...inspect certain portions
of Mr. Thatcher's unpublished memoirs.

220
00:16:50,800 --> 00:16:53,300
-l remember them.
-Yes, Jennings, I'll bring him in.

221
00:16:53,400 --> 00:16:55,900
-All I want is an hour--
-Under no circumstances...

222
00:16:55,900 --> 00:16:59,500
...are direct quotes from his manuscript
