00:44:33,100 --> 00:44:34,800
-l know I've a moustache.
-It looks awful.

685
00:44:34,900 --> 00:44:38,300
Have we got a society editor?

686
00:44:38,400 --> 00:44:41,200
-Right here, Mr. Kane.
-Miss Townsend is the society editor.

687
00:44:41,300 --> 00:44:43,900
Miss Townsend,
this is Mr. Charles Foster Kane.

688
00:44:45,000 --> 00:44:48,900
Miss Townsend, I've been away so long.
I don't know your routine.

689
00:44:50,100 --> 00:44:53,100
I got a little social announcement.

690
00:44:53,100 --> 00:44:56,900
I wish you wouldn't treat this
any differently than you would any other...

691
00:44:57,100 --> 00:44:58,700
...social announcement.

692
00:44:59,300 --> 00:45:02,300
Mr. Kane, on behalf of all the employees
{y:i}of the Inquirer--

693
00:45:02,300 --> 00:45:05,700
Mr. Bernstein,
thank you very much, everybody, l....

694
00:45:06,600 --> 00:45:10,500
I'm sorry, I can't accept it now.

695
00:45:10,700 --> 00:45:12,100
Goodbye.

696
00:45:12,700 --> 00:45:14,900
Say, he was in an awful hurry.

697
00:45:15,800 --> 00:45:17,800
Hey, everybody, look out here.

698
00:45:17,900 --> 00:45:19,800
Let's go to the window.

699
00:45:20,000 --> 00:45:22,800
-Mr. Leland! Mr. Bernstein!
-Yes, Ms. Townsend?

700
00:45:22,900 --> 00:45:25,600
This announcement:
"Mr. and Mrs. Thomas Monroe Norton...

701
00:45:25,700 --> 00:45:29,100
"...announce the engagement
of their daughter, Emily Monroe Norton...

702
00:45:29,200 --> 00:45:30,900
"...to Mr. Charles Foster Kane."

703
00:45:30,900 --> 00:45:32,400
Come on.

704
00:45:34,800 --> 00:45:39,500
Emily Monroe Norton, she's the niece
of the President of the United States.

705
00:45:39,700 --> 00:45:41,500
President's niece?

706
00:45:41,800 --> 00:45:45,000
Before he's through,
she'll be a president's wife.

707
00:45:53,000 --> 00:45:56,300
The way things turned out,
I don't need to tell you.

708
00:45:56,300 --> 00:45:58,900
Miss Emily Norton was no rosebud.

709
00:45:59,100 --> 00:46:01,100
It didn't end very well, did it?

710
00:46:01,500 --> 00:46:02,700
It ended.

711
00:46:03,700 --> 00:46:07,100
Then there was Susie. That ended, too.

712
00:46:09,300 --> 00:46:11,800
You know, Mr. Thompson, I was thinking...

713
00:46:12,600 --> 00:46:15,400
...this Rosebud
you're trying to find out about....

714
00:46:16,600 --> 00:46:17,900
Yes?

715
00:46:22,100 --> 00:46:24,400
Maybe that was something he lost.

716
00:46:25,200 --> 00:46:28,500
Mr. Kane was a man who lost
almost everything he had.

717
00:46:29,100 --> 00:46:31,300
You ought to see Jed Leland.

718
00:46:31,300 --> 00:46:34,400
Of course, he and Mr. Kane
didn't exactly see eye to eye.

719
00:46:34,500 --> 00:46:36,400
You take the Spanish-American war.

720
00:46:36,500 --> 00:46:39,700
I guess Mr. Leland was right.
That was Mr. Kane's war.

721
00:46:39,700 --> 00:46:42,600
We didn't really have anything
to fight about.

722
00:46:43,400 --> 00:46:46,800
Do you think if it hadn't been for that war
of Mr. Kane's...

723
00:46:47,100 --> 00:46:49,700
...we'd have the Panama Canal?

724
00:46:50,400 --> 00:46:52,800
I wish I knew where Mr. Leland was.

725
00:46:53,300 --> 00:46:56,400
A lot of the time now
they don't tell me these things.

726
00:46:57,600 --> 00:46:59,400
Maybe even he's dead.

727
00:46:59,500 --> 00:47:01,100
In case you'd like to know...

728
00:47:01,200 --> 00:47:04,100
...he's at the Huntington Memorial Hospital
on 180th Street.

729
00:47:04,100 --> 00:47:05,600
You don't say. I had--

730
00:47:05,600 --> 00:47:08,400
Nothing particular the matter with him,
they tell me, just....

731
00:47:08,500 --> 00:47:11,000
Just old age.

732
00:47:12,200 --> 00:47:16,900
It's the only disease that you don't
look forward to being cured of.

733
00:47:28,500 --> 00:47:31,300
I can remember absolutely everything,
young man.

734
00:47:31,400 --> 00:47:32,600
That's my curse.

735
00:47:32,700 --> 00:47:37,100
That's one of the greatest curses
ever inflicted on the human race: memory.

736
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:42,600
I was his oldest friend, and as far as
I was concerned, he behaved like a swine.

737
00:47:42,900 --> 00:47:46,800
Not that Charlie was ever brutal.
He just did brutal things.

738
00:47:47,500 --> 00:47:51,600
Maybe I wasn't his friend,
but if I wasn't, he never had one.

739
00:47:51,900 --> 00:47:55,300
Maybe I was what you nowadays
call a stooge.

740
00:47:55,400 --> 00:47:57,700
You were about to say something
about Rosebud.

741
00:47:57,700 --> 00:47:59,900
Do you happen to have a good cigar?

742
00:47:59,900 --> 00:48:03,700
I've got a young physician here
who thinks I'm going to give up smoking.

743
00:48:03,700 --> 00:48:05,900
No, I'm afraid I haven't. Sorry.

744
00:48:06,300 --> 00:48:07,900
I changed the subject, didn't l?

745
00:48:07,900 --> 00:48:10,300
What a disagreeable old man
I have become.

746
00:48:11,200 --> 00:48:15,900
You're a reporter and you want to know
what I think about Charlie Kane.

747
00:48:19,100 --> 00:48:21,600
I suppose he had some private sort
of greatness.

748
00:48:21,600 --> 00:48:23,300
But he kept it to himself.

749
00:48:23,400 --> 00:48:26,200
He never gave himself away.
He never gave anything away.

750
00:48:26,300 --> 00:48:29,100
He just left you a tip.

751
00:48:30,600 --> 00:48:31,900
He had a generous mind.

752
00:48:32,000 --> 00:48:35,000
I don't suppose anybody
ever had so many opinions.

753
00:48:35,300 --> 00:48:37,900
But he never believed in anything
except Charlie Kane.

754
00:48:38,000 --> 00:48:41,500
He never had a conviction
except Charlie Kane in his life.

755
00:48:41,700 --> 00:48:43,900
I suppose he died without one.

756
00:48:44,000 --> 00:48:46,500
That must have been pretty unpleasant.

757
00:48:46,800 --> 00:48:51,300
Of course, a lot of us check out without
having any special convictions about death.

758
00:48:51,400 --> 00:48:54,500
But we do know what we're leaving.
We do believe in something.

759
00:48:55,100 --> 00:48:58,100
Are you absolutely sure
you haven't got a cigar?

760
00:48:58,200 --> 00:49:00,100
-Sorry, Mr. Leland.
-Never mind.

761
00:49:00,200 --> 00:49:03,700
-What do you know about Rosebud?
-"Rosebud"?

762
00:49:04,600 --> 00:49:07,700
His dying words: "Rosebud."

763
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:10,100
{y:i}I saw that in the Inquirer.

764
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:13,900
I never believed anything
{y:i}I saw in the Inquirer.

765
00:49:13,900 --> 00:49:15,300
Anything else?

766
00:49:15,400 --> 00:49:18,900
I can tell you about Emily.
I went to dancing school with Emily.

767
00:49:19,300 --> 00:49:21,000
I was very graceful.

768
00:49:21,900 --> 00:49:25,200
-We were talking about the first Mrs. Kane.
-What was she like?

769
00:49:25,300 --> 00:49:27,700
She was like all the girls I knew
in dancing school.

770
00:49:27,700 --> 00:49:30,700
Very nice girl. Emily was a little nicer.

771
00:49:32,100 --> 00:49:34,100
After the first couple of months...

772
00:49:34,100 --> 00:49:38,300
...she and Charlie didn't see much
of each other except at breakfast.

773
00:49:38,900 --> 00:49:41,400
It was a marriage
just like any other marriage.

774
00:49:51,200 --> 00:49:52,900
-You're beautiful.
-l can't be.

775
00:49:52,900 --> 00:49:54,600
Yes, you are. You're very beautiful.

776
00:49:54,700 --> 00:49:57,100
I've never been to six parties
in one night before.

777
00:49:57,400 --> 00:50:00,000
-I've never been up this late.
-It痴 a matter of habit.

778
00:50:00,100 --> 00:50:02,900
-What will the servants think?
-That we enjoyed ourselves.

779
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:05,400
Why do you have to go straight off
to the newspaper?

780
00:50:05,500 --> 00:50:09,100
You never should've married a
newspaperman, they're worse than sailors.

781
00:50:09,900 --> 00:50:11,800
I absolutely adore you.

782
00:50:12,600 --> 00:50:15,400
Charles, even newspapermen
have to sleep.

783
00:50:16,800 --> 00:50:20,100
I'll call Mr. Bernstein and have him
put off my appointments till noon.

784
00:50:21,400 --> 00:50:22,400
What time is it?

785
00:50:23,100 --> 00:50:24,600
I don't know. It's late.

786
00:50:26,900 --> 00:50:28,800
It's early.

787
00:50:28,900 --> 00:50:30,500
Charles....

788
00:50:31,100 --> 00:50:33,900
Do you know how long
you kept me waiting last night...

789
00:50:34,000 --> 00:50:36,700
...when you went to the newspaper
for 10 minutes?

790
00:50:36,900 --> 00:50:40,000
What do you do in a newspaper
in the middle of the night?

791
00:50:40,100 --> 00:50:44,900
My dear, your only correspondent
{y:i}is the Inquirer.

792
00:50:45,000 --> 00:50:47,700
Sometimes I think I'd prefer a rival
of flesh and blood.

793
00:50:47,700 --> 00:50:50,200
I don't spend that much time
on the newspaper.

794
00:50:50,300 --> 00:50:54,200
It isn't just the time.
It's what you print, attacking the President.

795
00:50:54,300 --> 00:50:57,400
-You mean Uncle John.
-l mean the President of the United States.

796
00:50:57,500 --> 00:50:59,800
He's still Uncle John
and a well-meaning fathead...

797
00:50:59,900 --> 00:51:03,100
...who's letting a pack of high-pressure
crooks run his administration.

798
00:51:03,200 --> 00:51:06,900
-This whole oil scandal--
-He happens to be the President, not you.

799
00:51:06,900 --> 00:51:09,600
That's a mistake that will be corrected
one of these days.

800
00:51:09,700 --> 00:51:14,700
Your Mr. Bernstein sent Junior
the most incredible atrocity yesterday.

801
00:51:15,700 --> 00:51:18,300
I simply can't have it in the nursery.

802
00:51:20,300 --> 00:51:23,500
Mr. Bernstein is apt to pay a visit
to the nursery now and then.

803
00:51:23,500 --> 00:51:25,100
Does he have to?

804
00:51:26,100 --> 00:51:27,100
Yes.

805
00:51:27,200 --> 00:51:31,400
-Really, Charles, people will think--
-What I tell them to think.

806
00:51:49,500 --> 00:51:51,400
Wasn't he ever in love with her?

807
00:51:51,600 --> 00:51:53,300
He married for love.

808
00:51:54,100 --> 00:51:55,500
Love.

809
00:51:56,100 --> 00:51:57,700
That is why he did everything.

810
00:51:57,800 --> 00:52:00,700
That's why he went into politics.
It seems we weren't enough.

811
00:52:00,700 --> 00:52:03,700
He wanted all the voters to love him, too.

812
00:52:04,300 --> 00:52:06,700
All he wanted out of life was love.

813
00:52:07,500 --> 00:52:10,600
That's Charlie's story. How he lost it.

814
00:52:10,800 --> 00:52:13,900
You see, he just didn't have any to give.

815
00:52:14,900 --> 00:52:17,500
He loved Charlie Kane, of course.

816
00:52:18,100 --> 00:52:19,500
Very dearly.

817
00:52:20,200 --> 00:52:22,300
And his mother,
I guess he always loved her.

818
00:52:22,400 --> 00:52:25,300
-How about his second wife?
-Susan Alexander?

819
00:52:26,100 --> 00:52:28,100
You know what Charlie called her?

820
00:52:28,300 --> 00:52:31,000
The day after he'd met her,
he told me about her.

821
00:52:31,100 --> 00:52:35,900
He said she was
"a cross-section of the American public."

822
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:41,500
I guess he couldn't help it.
She must have had something for him.

823
00:52:41,600 --> 00:52:44,300
That first night, according to Charlie...

824
00:52:45,300 --> 00:52:47,500
...all she had was a toothache.

825
00:53:17,300 --> 00:53:19,700
What are you laughing at, young lady?

826
00:53:21,500 --> 00:53:24,200
-What's the matter with you?
-Toothache.

827
00:53:24,300 --> 00:53:25,900
-What?
-Toothache.

828
00:53:26,000 --> 00:53:27,300
Toothache?

829
00:53:30,600 --> 00:53:32,500
You mean you've got a toothache.

830
00:53:33,400 --> 00:53:36,200
-What's funny about that?
-You're funny, mister.

831
00:53:36,300 --> 00:53:38,700
-You've got dirt on your face.
-Not dirt, it's mud.

832
00:53:38,800 --> 00:53:41,000
Do you want some hot water?
I live right here.

833
00:53:41,100 --> 00:53:43,000
What's that, young lady?

834
00:53:44,200 --> 00:53:46,500
I said, if you wanted some hot water...

835
00:53:46,800 --> 00:53:50,800
...l could get you some...hot water.

836
00:53:54,300 --> 00:53:56,500
All right, thank you very much.

837
00:54:10,300 --> 00:54:12,100
Do I look any better now?

838
00:54:12,200 --> 00:54:16,700
-This medicine doesn't do a bit of good.
-What you need is to get your mind off it.

839
00:54:21,700 --> 00:54:24,700
Excuse me, but my landlady
prefers me to keep this door open...

840
00:54:24,900 --> 00:54:27,800
-...when I have a gentleman caller.
-All right.

841
00:54:27,900 --> 00:54:29,900
You have got a toothache, haven't you?

842
00:54:29,900 --> 00:54:32,900
-l surely have.
-Why don't you try laughing at me again?

843
00:54:33,000 --> 00:54:34,900
-What?
-I知 still pretty funny.

844
00:54:34,900 --> 00:54:37,400
I know, but you don't want me
to laugh at you.

845
00:54:37,500 --> 00:54:39,500
I don't want your tooth to hurt, either.

846
00:54:39,500 --> 00:54:40,800
Look at me.

847
00:54:41,200 --> 00:54:42,300
See that?

848
00:54:42,300 --> 00:54:43,600
What are you doing?

849
00:54:43,700 --> 00:54:46,100
I'm wiggling both my ears
at the same time.

850
00:54:48,200 --> 00:54:49,900
That's it, smile.

851
00:54:52,500 --> 00:54:56,100
It took me two solid years at the best
boys' school in the world to learn that.

852
00:54:56,200 --> 00:54:59,300
The fellow who taught me
is now president of Venezuela.

853
00:55:01,100 --> 00:55:02,500
That's it!

854
00:55:06,100 --> 00:55:08,600
-Is it a giraffe?
-No, not a giraffe.

855
00:55:08,700 --> 00:55:11,500
-l bet it is.
-What?

856
00:55:11,500 --> 00:55:13,600
Well, then it's an elephant.

857
00:55:13,800 --> 00:55:17,300
-It痴 supposed to be a rooster.
-A rooster!

858
00:55:17,800 --> 00:55:21,500
You know an awful lot of tricks.
Are you a professional magician?

859
00:55:21,600 --> 00:55:24,100
-No, I'm not a magician.
-l was just joking.

860
00:55:24,100 --> 00:55:25,700
You really don't know who I am?

861
00:55:25,800 --> 00:55:28,800
You told me your name, Mr. Kane,
but I'm awfully ignorant.

862
00:55:28,800 --> 00:55:33,100
I guess you caught on to that.
I bet I've heard your name a million times.

863
00:55:33,300 --> 00:55:36,300
You really like me, though,
even though you don't know who I am?

864
00:55:36,300 --> 00:55:39,700
I surely do. You've been wonderful.

865
00:55:40,700 --> 00:55:43,300
Without you I don't know
what I would have done.

866
00:55:43,400 --> 00:55:46,600
I had a toothache,
and I don't know many people.

867
00:55:46,900 --> 00:55:48,700
I know too many people.

868
00:55:49,100 --> 00:55:51,100
I guess we're both lonely.

869
00:55:51,400 --> 00:55:55,200
Want to know what I was going to do
before I ruined my best Sunday clothes?

870
00:55:55,200 --> 00:55:58,400
I bet they're not your best Sunday clothes.
You probably have more.

871
00:55:58,400 --> 00:55:59,600
I was just joking.

872
00:56:01,300 --> 00:56:05,000
I was on my way
to the Western Manhattan Warehouse...

873
00:56:05,100 --> 00:56:07,000
...in search of my youth.

874
00:56:08,100 --> 00:56:12,500
You see, my mother died a long time ago.
Her things were put in storage out West.

875
00:56:12,600 --> 00:56:14,900
There wasn't any other place to put them.

876
00:56:15,000 --> 00:56:18,900
I thought I'd send for them now.
Tonight I was going to take a look at them.

877
00:56:19,000 --> 00:56:21,100
A sort of sentimental journey.

878
00:56:24,500 --> 00:56:26,800
I run a couple of newspapers.
What do you do?

879
00:56:26,900 --> 00:56:27,800
Me?

880
00:56:28,100 --> 00:56:30,200
-How old did you say you were?
-l didn't say.

881
00:56:30,300 --> 00:56:32,900
If you had, I wouldn't have asked you.

882
00:56:33,000 --> 00:56:34,200
-How old?
-Pretty old.

883
00:56:34,300 --> 00:56:36,300
-How old?
-Twenty-two in August.

884
00:56:36,300 --> 00:56:38,300
That's a ripe old age. What do you do?

885
00:56:38,300 --> 00:56:41,700
I work at Seligman's.
I'm in charge of the sheet music.

886
00:56:41,900 --> 00:56:46,300
-Is that what you want to do?
-No, I wanted to be a singer, I guess.

887
00:56:47,100 --> 00:56:50,500
-That is, I didn't. My mother did for me.
-What happened to the singing?

888
00:56:50,600 --> 00:56:54,400
Mother always thought, she always talked
about grand opera for me.

889
00:56:54,500 --> 00:56:55,700
Imagine.

890
00:56:55,900 --> 00:57:00,000
But my voice isn't that kind.
It's just, you know what mothers are like.

891
00:57:01,700 --> 00:57:02,900
Yes.

892
00:57:04,800 --> 00:57:07,500
-Have you got a piano?
-A piano?

893
00:57:08,500 --> 00:57:10,200
Yes, there's one in the parlor.

894
00:57:10,300 --> 00:57:13,200
-Would you sing for me?
-You wouldn't want to hear me sing.

895
00:57:13,300 --> 00:57:14,600
Yes, I would.

896
00:57:16,300 --> 00:57:18,500
Don't tell me
your toothache is bothering you.

897
00:57:18,500 --> 00:57:20,200
No, that's all gone.

898
00:57:21,900 --> 00:57:23,700
All right.

899
00:57:24,700 --> 00:57:26,400
Let's go to the parlor.

900
00:57:26,400 --> 00:57:32,000
"Yes, Lindor shall be mine

901
00:57:33,300 --> 00:57:36,700
"l have sworn it

902
00:57:37,600 --> 00:57:40,300
"For weal or woe

903
00:57:42,300 --> 00:57:44,900
"Yes, Lindor

904
00:57:51,400 --> 00:57:54,600
{y:i}"Lo giurai

905
00:57:55,900 --> 00:57:59,700
{y:i}"La vincer?

906
00:58:07,400 --> 00:58:09,800
There is only one man
who can rid the politics...

907
00:58:09,800 --> 00:58:13,000
...of this state of the evil domination
of Boss Jim Gettys.

908
00:58:13,100 --> 00:58:16,800
I am speaking of Charles Foster Kane,
the fighting liberal...

909
00:58:16,900 --> 00:58:20,300
...the friend of the workingman,
the next governor of this state...

910
00:58:20,300 --> 00:58:22,500
...who entered upon this campaign....

911
00:58:22,600 --> 00:58:24,500
{y:i}...with one purpose only:

912
00:58:24,500 --> 00:58:28,700
{y:i}To point out
{y:i}and make public the dishonesty...

913
00:58:29,000 --> 00:58:33,600
{y:i}...the downright villainy
{y:i}of Boss Jim W. Gettys' political machine...

914
00:58:33,900 --> 00:58:38,000
{y:i}...now in complete control
{y:i}of the government of this state.

915
00:58:38,400 --> 00:58:42,100
{y:i}I made no campaign promises...

916
00:58:42,500 --> 00:58:47,000
{y:i}...because, until a few weeks ago,
{y:i}I had no hope of being elected.

917
00:58:48,500 --> 00:58:52,500
{y:i}Now, however, l have something more
{y:i}than a hope.

918
00:58:55,700 --> 00:58:58,100
{y:i}Jim Gettys has something less
{y:i}than a chance.

919
00:59:02,300 --> 00:59:04,100
{y:i}Every straw vote...

920
00:59:04,300 --> 00:59:08,900
{y:i}...every independent poll shows
{y:i}that l will be elected.

921
00:59:09,300 --> 00:59:11,000
{y:i}Very well.

922
00:59:11,100 --> 00:59:13,800
{y:i}Now l can afford to make some promises.

923
00:59:23,700 --> 00:59:25,700
{y:i}The workingman and the slum child...

924
00:59:25,800 --> 00:59:30,700
{y:i}...know they can expect
{y:i}my best efforts in their interests.

925
00:59:30,800 --> 00:59:35,200
{y:i}The decent, ordinary citizens know
{y:i}that I値l do everything in my power...

926
00:59:35,300 --> 00:59:40,300
{y:i}...to protect the underprivileged,
{y:i}the underpaid, and the underfed.

927
00:59:44,000 --> 00:59:48,200
-Mother, is Pop governor yet?
-Not yet, Junior.

928
00:59:51,900 --> 00:59:55,200
{y:i}I'd make my promises now...

929
00:59:55,500 --> 00:59:58,800
{y:i}...if I weren't too busy
{y:i}arranging to keep them.

930
01:00:03,200 --> 01:00:06,100
{y:i}But here's one promise I値l make...

931
01:00:06,100 --> 01:00:09,100
{y:i}...and Boss Jim Gettys knows I値l keep it.

932
01:00:10,300 --> 01:00:13,000
{y:i}My first official act
{y:i}as governor of this state...

933
01:00:13,400 --> 01:00:18,100
{y:i}...will be to appoint a special district
{y:i}attorney to arrange for the indictment...

934
01:00:18,300 --> 01:00:23,800
{y:i}...prosecution and conviction
{y:i}of Boss Jim W. Gettys.

935
01:00:48,900 --> 01:00:52,000
If the election were held today,
you'd be in by 100,000 votes.

936
01:00:52,100 --> 01:00:53,900
-Gettys isn't even pretending.
-Pop.

937
01:00:53,900 --> 01:00:56,000
-Hello, son.
-He isn't just scared, he's sick.

938
01:00:56,100 --> 01:00:58,800
It's beginning to dawn on Jim Gettys
I mean what I say.

939
01:00:58,900 --> 01:01:02,100
-Did you like your old man's speech?
-l could hear every word.

940
01:01:02,100 --> 01:01:03,700
-Hello, Emily.
-Hold it.

941
01:01:04,300 --> 01:01:06,900
-Great speech, Mr. Kane.
-Wonderful.

942
01:01:06,900 --> 01:01:09,100
Will you get us a taxi?

943
01:01:10,500 --> 01:01:13,300
I'm sending Junior home
in the car with Oliver.

944
01:01:13,600 --> 01:01:15,200
Good night, Father.

945
01:01:16,500 --> 01:01:18,300
Goodbye, son.

946
01:01:28,500 --> 01:01:31,800
Why did you send Junior home in the car?
What are you doing in a taxi?

947
01:01:31,900 --> 01:01:34,000
There's a call I want you to make with me.

948
01:01:34,100 --> 01:01:35,900
-It can wait.
-No, it can't.

949
01:01:36,000 --> 01:01:37,600
What's this all about, Emily?

950
01:01:37,700 --> 01:01:40,800
It may not be about anything at all.
I intend to find out.

951
01:01:40,900 --> 01:01:44,800
-Where are you going?
-I知 going to "185 West 74th Street."

952
01:01:46,300 --> 01:01:49,100
If you wish, you may come with me.

953
01:01:53,100 --> 01:01:54,500
I'll come with you.

954
01:01:59,500 --> 01:02:02,800
I had no idea you had this flair
for melodrama, Emily.

955
01:02:04,300 --> 01:02:06,300
Come right in, Mr. Kane.

956
01:02:16,400 --> 01:02:17,700
Charlie.

957
01:02:24,100 --> 01:02:27,100
He forced me to send your wife that letter.
I didn't want to.

958
01:02:27,200 --> 01:02:29,900
He's been saying the most terrible....

959
01:02:34,000 --> 01:02:35,600
Mrs. Kane.

960
01:02:37,500 --> 01:02:39,900
I don't suppose
anybody would introduce us.

961
01:02:41,300 --> 01:02:42,800
I'm Jim Gettys.

962
01:02:43,400 --> 01:02:44,500
Yes?

963
01:02:47,600 --> 01:02:51,200
I made Miss Alexander send you the note,
Mrs. Kane.

964
01:02:51,300 --> 01:02:53,500
She didn't want to at first. But she did it.

965
01:02:53,500 --> 01:02:56,200
Charlie, the things he said to me....
He threatened to--

966
01:02:57,300 --> 01:03:01,000
I won't wait until I'm elected.
To start with, I think I'll break your neck.

967
01:03:01,100 --> 01:03:03,700
Maybe you can do it, and maybe you can't.

968
01:03:04,700 --> 01:03:08,700
Your breaking this man's neck
would scarcely explain this note:

969
01:03:09,600 --> 01:03:13,300
"Serious consequences for Mr. Kane,
for yourself and for your son."

970
01:03:13,400 --> 01:03:16,300
-He wanted to get her to come here--
-What does this note mean?

971
01:03:16,300 --> 01:03:18,900
I'm Susan Alexander.
I know what you're thinking--

972
01:03:18,900 --> 01:03:21,600
-What does this note mean, Ms. Alexander?
-She don't know.

973
01:03:21,700 --> 01:03:24,400
She sent it because I told her
it wouldn't be smart not to.

974
01:03:24,500 --> 01:03:27,700
-Emily, this gentleman--
-I知 not a gentleman.

975
01:03:27,900 --> 01:03:30,600
Your husband is only trying to be funny
calling me one.

976
01:03:30,700 --> 01:03:33,200
I don't even know what a gentleman is.

977
01:03:34,200 --> 01:03:37,300
You see, my idea of a gentleman....

978
01:03:40,300 --> 01:03:43,700
If I owned a paper and didn't like
the way somebody was doing things...

979
01:03:43,700 --> 01:03:46,100
...some politician,
I'd fight him with all I had.

980
01:03:46,100 --> 01:03:47,900
I wouldn't show him in a convict suit...

981
01:03:47,900 --> 01:03:50,200
...so his family could see his picture
in the paper.

982
01:03:50,300 --> 01:03:54,100
-You're a cheap, crooked grafter--
-We're talking now about what you are.

983
01:03:54,900 --> 01:03:57,700
I'm fighting for my life,
not just my political life.

984
01:03:57,700 --> 01:03:59,800
-He said unless you--
-That's what I said.

985
01:03:59,900 --> 01:04:03,700
Here's the chance I'm willing to give him.
It's more of a chance than he'd give me.

986
01:04:03,800 --> 01:04:08,400
Unless he decides by tomorrow that
he's so sick he has to go away for a year...

987
01:04:08,500 --> 01:04:12,600
...Monday morning, all papers in the state,
except his, will carry the story I'll give.

988
01:04:12,700 --> 01:04:14,000
What story?

989
01:04:14,700 --> 01:04:17,800
-The story about him and Ms. Alexander.
-There isn't any story!

990
01:04:17,900 --> 01:04:19,000
Shut up.

991
01:04:19,400 --> 01:04:22,100
We've got evidence that would look bad
in the headlines.

992
01:04:22,100 --> 01:04:24,700
Do you want me to give you the evidence?

993
01:04:26,700 --> 01:04:29,500
I'd rather he withdrew
without having the story published.

994
01:04:29,500 --> 01:04:32,500
Not that I care about him,
but I'd be better off that way.

995
01:04:35,300 --> 01:04:37,300
So would you, Mrs. Kane.

996
01:04:37,700 --> 01:04:39,700
What about me?

997
01:04:41,600 --> 01:04:45,300
He said my name would be dragged
through the mud. That everywhere I went--

998
01:04:45,300 --> 01:04:48,100
There seems to be only one decision
you can make, Charles.

999
01:04:48,700 --> 01:04:50,700
I'd say that it'd been made for you.

1000
01:04:52,300 --> 01:04:54,300
You can't tell me the voters of this state--

1001
01:04:54,600 --> 01:04:57,300
I'm not interested in the voters
of this state right now.

1002
01:04:57,300 --> 01:04:58,700
I am interested in our son.

1003
01:04:58,800 --> 01:05:01,800
-Charlie, if they publish this story--
-They won't.

1004
01:05:03,100 --> 01:05:05,100
Good night, Mr. Gettys.

1005
01:05:13,700 --> 01:05:15,700
Are you coming, Charles?

1006
01:05:17,800 --> 01:05:19,100
No.

1007
01:05:22,400 --> 01:05:23,900
I'm staying here.

1008
01:05:26,900 --> 01:05:28,900
I can fight this all alone.

1009
01:05:30,100 --> 01:05:32,500
If you don't listen to reason,
it may be too late.

1010
01:05:32,600 --> 01:05:36,400
Too late? For what?

1011
01:05:38,400 --> 01:05:41,600
For you and this public thief...

1012
01:05:41,900 --> 01:05:44,100
...to take the love of the people
away from me?

1013
01:05:44,200 --> 01:05:46,900
You got other things to think about.
Your little boy.

1014
01:05:47,000 --> 01:05:49,300
You don't want him to read about you
in the papers.

1015
01:05:49,400 --> 01:05:53,700
There's only one person in the world
to decide what I'll do. And that's me.

1016
01:05:56,500 --> 01:05:59,900
You decided what you were going to do,
Charles, some time ago.

1017
01:06:06,900 --> 01:06:09,400
You're making a bigger fool of yourself
than I thought.

1018
01:06:09,500 --> 01:06:11,700
-I致e got nothing to say to you.
-You're licked--

1019
01:06:11,800 --> 01:06:15,100
Get out. If you want to see me,
have the warden write me a letter.

1020
01:06:15,300 --> 01:06:19,800
If it was anybody else, I'd say what's going
to happen to you would be a lesson to you.

1021
01:06:20,000 --> 01:06:22,600
Only you're going to need
more than one lesson.

1022
01:06:23,400 --> 01:06:27,300
-And you'll get more than one lesson.
-Don't worry about me, Gettys.

1023
01:06:28,900 --> 01:06:30,900
Don't worry about me!

1024
01:06:31,700 --> 01:06:34,200
I'm Charles Foster Kane!

1025
01:06:34,800 --> 01:06:38,900
I'm no cheap, crooked politician
trying to save himself...

1026
01:06:38,900 --> 01:06:41,900
...from the consequences of his crimes!

1027
01:06:42,900 --> 01:06:46,700
Gettys! I'm gonna send you to Sing Sing.

1028
01:06:46,900 --> 01:06:48,900
Sing Sing, Gettys.

1029
01:06:52,000 --> 01:06:55,000
-Have you a car, Mrs. Kane?
-Yes, thank you.

1030
01:06:55,500 --> 01:06:58,100
-Good night.
-Good night.

1031
01:07:08,500 --> 01:07:12,300
{y:i}Paper. Read all about it. Extra, extra.

1032
01:07:16,700 --> 01:07:18,700
-Paper?
-No, thanks.

1033
01:07:32,900 --> 01:07:35,700
With a million majority
already against him...

1034
01:07:35,900 --> 01:07:39,100
...and the church counties
still to be heard from...

1035
01:07:39,300 --> 01:07:41,600
...I知 afraid we got no choice.

1036
01:07:41,700 --> 01:07:43,100
This one?

1037
01:07:46,400 --> 01:07:48,100
That one.

1038
01:08:10,400 --> 01:08:12,200
Good night again.

1039
01:08:22,900 --> 01:08:26,200
-Is there anything I can--
-No, thanks, Mr. Bernstein.

1040
01:08:27,800 --> 01:08:30,000
You better go home and get some sleep.

1041
01:08:31,100 --> 01:08:32,500
You, too.

1042
01:08:34,800 --> 01:08:36,500
Good night, Mr. Kane.

1043
01:09:00,600 --> 01:09:03,100
-Hello, Jedediah.
-I知 drunk.

1044
01:09:06,600 --> 01:09:11,500
If you've got drunk to talk to me about...

1045
01:09:13,900 --> 01:09:16,400
...Ms. Alexander, don't bother.

1046
01:09:18,100 --> 01:09:19,900
I'm not interested.

1047
01:09:23,900 --> 01:09:27,600
I've set back the sacred cause of reform,
is that it?

1048
01:09:29,000 --> 01:09:30,400
All right.

1049
01:09:32,100 --> 01:09:35,200
If that's the way they want it,
the people have made their choice.

1050
01:09:35,300 --> 01:09:38,000
It's obvious the people prefer
Jim Gettys to me.

1051
01:09:38,100 --> 01:09:41,600
You talk about the people
as though you owned them.

1052
01:09:41,700 --> 01:09:43,900
As though they belong to you. Goodness.

1053
01:09:44,600 --> 01:09:49,200
As long as I can remember, you've talked
about giving the people their rights...

1054
01:09:49,300 --> 01:09:52,500
...as if you could make them
a present of liberty...

1055
01:09:52,600 --> 01:09:55,000
...as a reward for services rendered.

1056
01:09:55,100 --> 01:09:57,400
-Jed.
-You remember the workingman?

1057
01:09:58,100 --> 01:10:00,600
I'll get drunk, too, Jedediah...

1058
01:10:02,100 --> 01:10:03,300
...if it'll do any good.

1059
01:10:03,300 --> 01:10:06,600
It won't do any good.
Besides you never get drunk.

1060
01:10:06,700 --> 01:10:09,500
You used to write an awful lot
about the workingman--

1061
01:10:09,500 --> 01:10:10,400
Go on home.

1062
01:10:10,400 --> 01:10:13,200
He's turning into something called
"organized labor."

1063
01:10:14,900 --> 01:10:18,100
You won't like that one little bit
when you find out...

1064
01:10:18,200 --> 01:10:23,100
...it means your workingman expects
something as his right, and not your gift.

1065
01:10:25,100 --> 01:10:29,400
When your precious underprivileged
really get together....

1066
01:10:30,000 --> 01:10:31,700
Oh, boy....

1067
01:10:32,500 --> 01:10:35,300
That'll add up to something
bigger than your privilege...

1068
01:10:35,400 --> 01:10:38,300
...then I don't know what you'll do.

1069
01:10:38,300 --> 01:10:43,400
Sail away to a desert island probably
and lord it over the monkeys.

1070
01:10:44,600 --> 01:10:46,700
I wouldn't worry about it too much.

1071
01:10:47,100 --> 01:10:51,700
There'll probably be a few of them there
to tell me when I do something wrong.

1072
01:10:51,900 --> 01:10:53,900
You may not always be so lucky.

1073
01:10:54,700 --> 01:10:56,100
You're not very drunk.

1074
01:10:56,200 --> 01:10:58,100
Drunk, what do you care?

1075
01:10:58,500 --> 01:11:01,300
You don't care about anything except you.

1076
01:11:02,300 --> 01:11:07,900
You persuade people that you love them
so much that they ought to love you back.

1077
01:11:08,200 --> 01:11:10,700
Only you want love on your own terms.

1078
01:11:12,300 --> 01:11:15,700
It's something to be played your way,
according to your rules.

1079
01:11:22,000 --> 01:11:25,100
-Let me work on the Chicago paper.
-What?

1080
01:11:25,400 --> 01:11:30,000
You said you were looking for someone
to do dramatic "crimitism," criticism.

1081
01:11:30,200 --> 01:11:31,900
I am drunk.

1082
01:11:34,300 --> 01:11:36,200
I want to go to Chicago.

1083
01:11:37,500 --> 01:11:39,100
You're too valuable here.

1084
01:11:41,300 --> 01:11:45,100
-There's nothing left for me to do--
-All right, you can go to Chicago.

1085
01:11:45,200 --> 01:11:46,400
Thank you.

1086
01:11:47,400 --> 01:11:49,900
I guess I'd better try to get drunk anyway.

1087
01:11:51,500 --> 01:11:53,900
I warn you, Jedediah,
you won't like Chicago.

1088
01:11:53,900 --> 01:11:58,400
The wind comes off the lake, and they've
probably never heard of Lobster Newburg.

1089
01:11:58,500 --> 01:12:00,600
Will Saturday after next be all right?

1090
01:12:00,700 --> 01:12:02,500
-Anytime you say.
-Thank you.

1091
01:12:08,000 --> 01:12:12,800
A toast to love on my terms.
Those are the only terms anybody knows:

1092
01:12:14,300 --> 01:12:15,500
His own.

1093
01:12:27,900 --> 01:12:30,300
{y:i}Mr. Kane, I'm from the Inquirer.

1094
01:12:39,200 --> 01:12:42,000
-What's that, young man?
-Are you through with politics?

1095
01:12:42,100 --> 01:12:44,700
Am I through with politics?
I would say vice versa.

1096
01:12:46,000 --> 01:12:47,700
We're going to be an opera star.

1097
01:12:47,700 --> 01:12:49,500
Are you singing at the Metropolitan?

1098
01:12:49,600 --> 01:12:50,900
We certainly are.

1099
01:12:51,100 --> 01:12:53,800
Charlie said if I didn't,
he'd build me an opera house.

1100
01:12:53,900 --> 01:12:55,300
That won't be necessary.

1101
01:13:00,000 --> 01:13:03,200
No, no, no!

1102
01:13:35,400 --> 01:13:36,800
Places, please!

1103
01:14:23,900 --> 01:14:26,600
Mr. Leland is writing it
from the dramatic angle?

1104
01:14:26,700 --> 01:14:30,000
-And we've covered it from the news end.
-And the social.

1105
01:14:30,800 --> 01:14:32,900
How about the music notice?

1106
01:14:33,000 --> 01:14:34,900
Yes, it's already made up.

1107
01:14:35,000 --> 01:14:37,500
Mr. Mowan wrote a swell review.

1108
01:14:39,000 --> 01:14:43,000
-Enthusiastic?
-Yes, sir.

1109
01:14:43,100 --> 01:14:45,700
Mr. Kane. This is a surprise.

1110
01:14:48,100 --> 01:14:50,100
We've got two spreads of pictures.

1111
01:14:50,100 --> 01:14:51,900
The music notice on the front page?

1112
01:14:52,000 --> 01:14:55,500
But there's still one notice to come.
The dramatic.

1113
01:14:56,600 --> 01:14:58,100
The dramatic notice.

1114
01:14:59,200 --> 01:15:03,500
-Mr. Bernstein, that's Mr. Leland, isn't it?
-Yes, we're waiting for it.

1115
01:15:07,300 --> 01:15:10,200
-Where is he?
-Right in there, Mr. Kane.

1116
01:15:17,800 --> 01:15:19,200
Mr. Kane.

1117
01:15:33,400 --> 01:15:36,000
Mr. Leland and Mr. Kane...

1118
01:15:37,100 --> 01:15:40,200
...haven't spoken together for years.

1119
01:15:42,700 --> 01:15:45,300
-You don't suppose--
-There's nothing to suppose.

1120
01:15:49,500 --> 01:15:50,700
Excuse me.

1121
01:16:07,100 --> 01:16:08,500
Close the door.

1122
01:16:11,700 --> 01:16:14,100
He ain't been drinking before.

1123
01:16:15,000 --> 01:16:17,000
Never. We would have heard.

1124
01:16:17,300 --> 01:16:19,200
What does it say there?

1125
01:16:19,700 --> 01:16:22,200
The notice, what's he written?

1126
01:16:23,900 --> 01:16:28,600
"Miss Susan Alexander, a pretty
but hopelessly incompetent amateur...

1127
01:16:32,000 --> 01:16:35,700
"...last night opened
the new Chicago Opera House...

1128
01:16:36,000 --> 01:16:37,700
"...in a performance of...."

1129
01:16:40,700 --> 01:16:44,100
I still can't pronounce that name.

1130
01:16:47,400 --> 01:16:51,200
"Her singing, happily,
is no concern of this department.

1131
01:16:51,600 --> 01:16:55,400
"Of her acting,
it is absolutely impossible to...."

1132
01:16:57,000 --> 01:16:58,100
Go on.

1133
01:17:00,500 --> 01:17:02,400
That's all there is.

1134
01:17:15,000 --> 01:17:18,400
Of her acting it is absolutely
impossible to say anything except...

1135
01:17:18,500 --> 01:17:21,900
...that, in the opinion of this reviewer,
it represents a new low.

1136
01:17:22,100 --> 01:17:24,900
-In the opinion of this reviewer.
-l didn't see that.

1137
01:17:25,000 --> 01:17:27,200
It isn't here, Mr. Bernstein, I'm dictating it.

1138
01:17:27,300 --> 01:17:30,100
-Mr. Kane, l--
-Get me a typewriter.

1139
01:17:31,500 --> 01:17:33,800
I'm going to finish Mr. Leland's notice.

1140
01:17:50,200 --> 01:17:52,000
Hello, Bernstein.

1141
01:17:56,900 --> 01:18:00,100
-Hello.
-Hello, Mr. Leland.

1142
01:18:03,300 --> 01:18:06,400
Where's my notice, Bernstein?
I've got to finish my notice.

1143
01:18:06,500 --> 01:18:09,600
-Mr. Kane is finishing it for you.
-Charlie?

1144
01:18:15,300 --> 01:18:17,600
Charlie out there?

1145
01:18:19,300 --> 01:18:21,600
I guess he's fixing it up.

1146
01:18:23,900 --> 01:18:26,300
I knew I'd never get that through.

1147
01:18:27,100 --> 01:18:30,900
Mr. Kane's finishing your review
just the way you started it.

1148
01:18:31,300 --> 01:18:34,900
He's writing a bad notice
like you wanted it to be.

1149
01:18:37,300 --> 01:18:39,200
I guess that'll show you.

1150
01:19:03,100 --> 01:19:04,900
Hello, Jedediah.

1151
