And left you?

1391
01:40:09,100 --> 01:40:10,900
Of course they'll hear.

1392
01:40:11,900 --> 01:40:14,400
I'm not saying goodbye, except to you.

1393
01:40:14,600 --> 01:40:17,300
But I never imagined
people wouldn't know.

1394
01:40:19,700 --> 01:40:21,500
I won't let you go.

1395
01:40:28,500 --> 01:40:30,100
Goodbye, Charlie.

1396
01:40:33,500 --> 01:40:34,900
Susan.

1397
01:40:44,700 --> 01:40:46,200
Please don't go.

1398
01:40:51,600 --> 01:40:53,300
Please, Susan.

1399
01:40:56,400 --> 01:40:59,700
From now on, everything will be
exactly the way you want it to be.

1400
01:40:59,800 --> 01:41:01,900
Not the way I think you want it, but...

1401
01:41:03,500 --> 01:41:04,900
...your way.

1402
01:41:11,100 --> 01:41:12,400
You mustn't go.

1403
01:41:15,500 --> 01:41:17,600
You can't do this to me.

1404
01:41:19,200 --> 01:41:20,800
I see.

1405
01:41:21,700 --> 01:41:24,100
It's you that this is being done to.

1406
01:41:24,500 --> 01:41:26,200
It's not me at all.

1407
01:41:26,400 --> 01:41:28,300
Not what it means to me.

1408
01:41:30,300 --> 01:41:32,400
I can't do this to you?

1409
01:41:33,800 --> 01:41:35,700
Oh, yes, I can.

1410
01:41:54,100 --> 01:41:57,100
In case you haven't heard,
I lost all my money and it was plenty.

1411
01:41:57,100 --> 01:41:59,300
The last 10 years
have been difficult for many.

1412
01:41:59,400 --> 01:42:02,300
They haven't been tough on me.
I just lost all my money.

1413
01:42:02,900 --> 01:42:05,900
-You're going down to Xanadu?
-Monday, with boys from the office.

1414
01:42:05,900 --> 01:42:08,600
Mr. Rawlston wants
the whole place photographed.

1415
01:42:08,700 --> 01:42:10,200
We run a picture magazine.

1416
01:42:10,300 --> 01:42:13,900
If you're smart, you'll get in touch
with Raymond. He's the butler.

1417
01:42:13,900 --> 01:42:15,800
You'll learn a lot from him.

1418
01:42:15,900 --> 01:42:18,300
He knows where all the bodies are buried.

1419
01:42:18,500 --> 01:42:21,500
You know, all the same,
I feel kind of sorry for Mr. Kane.

1420
01:42:23,700 --> 01:42:25,300
Don't you think I do?

1421
01:42:29,700 --> 01:42:32,500
What do you know, it's morning already.

1422
01:42:35,900 --> 01:42:39,300
Come around and tell me the story
of your life sometime.

1423
01:42:46,100 --> 01:42:47,600
Rosebud?

1424
01:42:50,100 --> 01:42:52,100
I'll tell you about Rosebud.

1425
01:42:52,600 --> 01:42:54,400
How much is it worth to you?

1426
01:42:55,000 --> 01:42:56,700
$1,000?

1427
01:43:05,600 --> 01:43:08,200
Well, I'll tell you, Mr. Thompson.

1428
01:43:08,900 --> 01:43:12,200
-He acted funny sometimes, you know?
-No, I didn't.

1429
01:43:12,400 --> 01:43:14,700
Yes, he did crazy things sometimes.

1430
01:43:15,100 --> 01:43:17,400
I've been working for him 11 years now...

1431
01:43:17,500 --> 01:43:21,100
...in charge of the whole place,
so I ought to know.

1432
01:43:21,500 --> 01:43:22,700
-Rosebud.
-Yes.

1433
01:43:22,700 --> 01:43:27,500
Like I tell you, the old man
acted kind of funny sometimes...

1434
01:43:27,600 --> 01:43:31,200
-...but I knew how to handle him--
-Need a lot of service?

1435
01:43:31,300 --> 01:43:34,200
But I knew how to handle him.

1436
01:43:34,300 --> 01:43:35,900
Like that time his wife left.

1437
01:45:46,100 --> 01:45:47,300
Rosebud.

1438
01:46:52,600 --> 01:46:54,100
I see.

1439
01:46:54,700 --> 01:46:57,100
And that's what you know about Rosebud?

1440
01:46:58,500 --> 01:47:00,800
I heard him say it that other time, too.

1441
01:47:01,500 --> 01:47:03,300
He just said:

1442
01:47:03,700 --> 01:47:05,400
"Rosebud."

1443
01:47:05,500 --> 01:47:08,600
Then he dropped the glass ball
and it broke on the floor.

1444
01:47:09,300 --> 01:47:13,300
He didn't say anything after that,
and I knew he was dead.

1445
01:47:14,100 --> 01:47:16,700
He said all kinds of things
that didn't mean anything.

1446
01:47:16,700 --> 01:47:18,700
Sentimental fellow, aren't you?

1447
01:47:19,700 --> 01:47:22,300
-Yes and no.
-That isn't worth $1,000.

1448
01:47:22,300 --> 01:47:25,200
You can keep on asking questions
if you want to.

1449
01:47:25,500 --> 01:47:27,100
We're leaving tonight...

1450
01:47:27,800 --> 01:47:29,700
...when we're through taking pictures.

1451
01:47:29,800 --> 01:47:31,700
Allow yourself plenty of time.

1452
01:47:31,700 --> 01:47:35,400
The train stops at the junction on signal,
but they don't like to wait.

1453
01:47:36,400 --> 01:47:39,300
I can remember when they'd wait all day...

1454
01:47:39,600 --> 01:47:41,200
...if Mr. Kane said so.

1455
01:47:42,600 --> 01:47:45,100
Better get going.

1456
01:47:47,900 --> 01:47:51,700
-Can we come down?
-Yes, hurry up. We're leaving.

1457
01:47:53,800 --> 01:47:57,100
How much do you think
this is all worth, Mr. Thompson?

1458
01:47:57,300 --> 01:47:58,800
Millions.

1459
01:48:00,200 --> 01:48:01,400
If anybody wants it.

1460
01:48:01,500 --> 01:48:04,000
Well, at least he brought all this stuff
to America.

1461
01:48:04,100 --> 01:48:05,800
-What's that?
-Another Venus.

1462
01:48:05,900 --> 01:48:07,100
$25,000.

1463
01:48:07,200 --> 01:48:09,700
A lot of money to pay
for a dame without a head.

1464
01:48:09,800 --> 01:48:11,900
The banks are out of luck?

1465
01:48:13,300 --> 01:48:15,900
-They'll clear all right.
-He never threw anything away.

1466
01:48:16,000 --> 01:48:21,000
"Welcome home, Mr. Kane, from 467
{y:i}employees of the New York Inquirer."

1467
01:48:21,100 --> 01:48:26,200
"One stove from the estate of Mary Kane,
Little Salem, Colorado. Value: $2."

1468
01:48:26,300 --> 01:48:28,700
We're supposed to get everything,
junk as well as art.

1469
01:48:28,700 --> 01:48:30,400
He sure liked to collect things.

1470
01:48:30,400 --> 01:48:31,800
Anything and everything.

1471
01:48:31,900 --> 01:48:33,500
A regular crow, eh?

1472
01:48:33,600 --> 01:48:36,200
-Hey, look, a jigsaw puzzle.
-We got a lot of those.

1473
01:48:36,300 --> 01:48:39,200
A Burmese temple and three
Spanish ceilings down the hall.

1474
01:48:39,700 --> 01:48:41,100
Part of a Scotch castle...

1475
01:48:41,100 --> 01:48:42,900
...that needs to be unwrapped.

1476
01:48:43,200 --> 01:48:44,600
Put all this stuff together:

1477
01:48:44,700 --> 01:48:47,700
The palaces and the paintings,
and the toys and everything.

1478
01:48:47,800 --> 01:48:49,700
What would it spell?

1479
01:48:51,100 --> 01:48:53,700
-Charles Foster Kane?
-Or Rosebud.

1480
01:48:54,000 --> 01:48:57,100
-How about it, Jerry?
-What's Rosebud?

1481
01:48:57,200 --> 01:48:59,300
That's what he said when he died.

1482
01:49:00,000 --> 01:49:02,100
Did you ever find out what it means?

1483
01:49:02,100 --> 01:49:04,300
-No, I didn't.
-What did you find out about him?

1484
01:49:04,300 --> 01:49:05,700
Not much, really.

1485
01:49:08,700 --> 01:49:10,400
We'd better get started.

1486
01:49:12,200 --> 01:49:14,500
What have you been doing all this time?

1487
01:49:15,500 --> 01:49:17,100
Playing with a jigsaw puzzle.

1488
01:49:17,100 --> 01:49:20,800
If you'd discovered what Rosebud meant,
I bet it would've explained everything.

1489
01:49:20,800 --> 01:49:22,300
No, I don't think so.

1490
01:49:22,900 --> 01:49:24,300
No.

1491
01:49:24,400 --> 01:49:27,800
He was a man who got
everything he wanted, and then lost it.

1492
01:49:27,900 --> 01:49:31,500
Maybe Rosebud was something
he couldn't get or something he lost.

1493
01:49:31,500 --> 01:49:33,700
It wouldn't have explained anything.

1494
01:49:34,600 --> 01:49:37,600
I don't think any word
can explain a man's life.

1495
01:49:38,500 --> 01:49:42,500
No. I guess Rosebud is just a piece
in a jigsaw puzzle.

1496
01:49:43,700 --> 01:49:45,300
A missing piece.

1497
01:49:50,900 --> 01:49:53,000
Come on, everybody...

1498
01:49:54,700 --> 01:49:56,900
...we'll miss the train.

1499
01:50:58,900 --> 01:51:01,100
Throw that junk in.

1500
01:52:33,700 --> 01:52:37,600
Maybe I was what you nowadays
call a stooge.

1501
01:52:38,200 --> 01:52:40,100
Everything was his idea...

1502
01:52:42,000 --> 01:52:43,900
...except my leaving him.

1503
01:52:44,800 --> 01:52:46,700
I've got his trunk all packed.

1504
01:52:47,900 --> 01:52:50,000
I've had it packed for a week now.

1505
01:52:50,300 --> 01:52:53,600
Sometimes I think I'd prefer
a rival of flesh and blood.

1506
01:52:55,200 --> 01:52:57,600
You're gonna need more than one lesson.

1507
01:52:58,700 --> 01:53:01,100
And you'll get more than one lesson.

1508
01:53:06,200 --> 01:53:07,600
Who's a busy man, me?

1509
01:53:07,900 --> 01:53:11,000
I'm chairman of the board.
I got nothing but time.

1510
01:53:11,200 --> 01:53:12,600
What do you want to know?

1511
01:53:12,700 --> 01:53:17,100
We thought.... If we could find out what he
meant by his last words as he was dying....

1512
01:53:17,600 --> 01:53:19,700
Sentimental fellow, aren't you?

1513
01:53:21,000 --> 01:53:22,100
Yes and no.

1514
01:53:22,400 --> 01:53:25,100
"l think it would be fun
to run a newspaper."

1515
01:53:25,500 --> 01:53:28,900
"l think it would be fun
to run a newspaper."


